{
  "In anatomical position, the palms face:": "",
  "Anteriorly (forward)": "",
  "Posteriorly": "",
  "Inferiorly": "",
  "Medially": "",
  "In standard anatomical position, the body stands erect with feet slightly apart, arms at the sides, and palms facing forward (anteriorly), which serves as the universal reference point for describing body structures.": "",
  "The sagittal plane divides the body into:": "",
  "Left and right portions": "",
  "Front and back halves": "",
  "Upper and lower halves": "",
  "Inside and outside": "",
  "A sagittal plane runs vertically through the body from front to back, dividing it into left and right portions, with a midsagittal (median) plane creating equal halves.": "",
  "The frontal (coronal) plane divides the body into:": "",
  "Medial and lateral portions": "",
  "Upper and lower portions": "",
  "Anterior and posterior portions": "",
  "The frontal (coronal) plane runs vertically from side to side, dividing the body into front (anterior) and back (posterior) portions.": "",
  "The transverse plane creates which type of section?": "",
  "A longitudinal section": "",
  "A frontal section": "",
  "A sagittal section": "",
  "A cross-section dividing upper and lower portions": "",
  "The transverse (horizontal) plane runs horizontally through the body, creating a cross-section that divides the body into superior (upper) and inferior (lower) portions.": "",
  "The elbow is _____ to the wrist.": "",
  "Lateral": "",
  "Inferior": "",
  "Distal": "",
  "Proximal": "",
  "Proximal means closer to the point of attachment to the trunk, so the elbow is proximal to the wrist because it is closer to the shoulder where the limb attaches.": "",
  "The cranial cavity houses the:": "",
  "Stomach": "",
  "Brain": "",
  "Lungs": "",
  "Heart": "",
  "The cranial cavity is formed by the bones of the skull and serves as a protective enclosure for the brain, which is part of the dorsal body cavity.": "",
  "The thoracic cavity contains the:": "",
  "Reproductive organs": "",
  "Heart and lungs": "",
  "Brain and spinal cord": "",
  "Stomach only": "",
  "The thoracic cavity is located in the chest and contains the heart (within the mediastinum), the lungs (within the pleural cavities), and major blood vessels.": "",
  "The nose is _____ to the ears.": "",
  "Superior": "",
  "Medial": "",
  "Medial means closer to the midline of the body, and since the nose is on the midline while the ears are on the sides, the nose is medial to the ears.": "",
  "Anterior is the same directional term as:": "",
  "Ventral": "",
  "Dorsal": "",
  "In human anatomy, anterior (front) and ventral (belly side) are synonymous, just as posterior (back) and dorsal (back side) are synonymous.": "",
  "The diaphragm separates which two cavities?": "",
  "Pelvic and abdominal": "",
  "Dorsal and cranial": "",
  "Cranial and vertebral": "",
  "Thoracic and abdominal": "",
  "The diaphragm is a dome-shaped muscle that forms the floor of the thoracic cavity and the roof of the abdominal cavity, physically separating these two major ventral body cavities.": "",
  "What is the anatomical position?": "",
  "Sitting with legs crossed and arms folded": "",
  "Lying face down with arms at the sides": "",
  "Standing erect, facing forward, arms at sides, palms facing forward, feet slightly apart": "",
  "Lying on the back with palms facing down": "",
  "The anatomical position is the standard reference posture: standing erect, facing forward, feet slightly apart, arms at the sides with palms facing anteriorly. All directional terms are based on this position.": "",
  "What does the term 'superior' mean in anatomy?": "",
  "Away from the midline": "",
  "Closer to the body surface": "",
  "Toward the back of the body": "",
  "Toward the head or upper part of the body": "",
  "Superior (cranial or cephalad) means toward the head or the upper part of a structure, so the heart is superior to the stomach because it is closer to the head.": "",
  "What does 'proximal' mean?": "",
  "Toward the midline of the body": "",
  "Toward the surface of the body": "",
  "Farther from the trunk or point of origin of a limb": "",
  "Closer to the trunk or point of origin of a limb": "",
  "Proximal means nearer to the point of attachment of a limb to the trunk, so the shoulder is proximal to the elbow, which in turn is proximal to the wrist.": "",
  "What is the dorsal body cavity?": "",
  "The cavity containing the reproductive organs": "",
  "The cavity containing the abdominal organs": "",
  "The posterior cavity that includes the cranial cavity and the vertebral (spinal) canal": "",
  "The cavity containing the heart and lungs": "",
  "The dorsal body cavity is located along the posterior (back) side of the body and consists of two subdivisions: the cranial cavity (enclosing the brain) and the vertebral canal (enclosing the spinal cord).": "",
  "What does 'superficial' mean in anatomical terms?": "",
  "Toward the feet": "",
  "Closer to or on the body surface": "",
  "Farther from the body surface, toward the interior": "",
  "Superficial means closer to or at the surface of the body, while its opposite, deep, means farther from the surface. For example, the skin is superficial to the muscles beneath it.": "",
  "What is the ventral body cavity?": "",
  "The cavity enclosing only the brain": "",
  "The cavity enclosing only the spinal cord": "",
  "The space between the skin and the muscles": "",
  "The anterior cavity that includes the thoracic and abdominopelvic cavities": "",
  "The ventral (anterior) body cavity is the larger of the two main body cavities, subdivided into the thoracic cavity (above the diaphragm) and the abdominopelvic cavity (below the diaphragm).": "",
  "What does the term 'prone' mean?": "",
  "Lying face up on the back": "",
  "Sitting upright with arms extended": "",
  "Standing in anatomical position": "",
  "Lying face down on the abdomen": "",
  "Prone describes a body position in which a person is lying face down on their abdomen, while supine is the opposite position of lying face up on the back.": "",
  "What does 'lateral' mean?": "",
  "Away from the midline of the body, toward the side": "",
  "Toward the head": "",
  "Lateral means farther from the midline or toward the side of the body. For example, the ears are lateral to the nose because they are farther from the body's central axis.": "",
  "What is the abdominopelvic cavity?": "",
  "The portion of the ventral cavity below the diaphragm, divided into abdominal and pelvic regions": "",
  "The cavity above the diaphragm containing the heart": "",
  "The posterior cavity housing the brain and spinal cord": "",
  "The space inside the ribcage only": "",
  "The abdominopelvic cavity lies below the diaphragm and is subdivided into the abdominal cavity (containing the stomach, liver, intestines, and other organs) and the pelvic cavity (containing the bladder, reproductive organs, and rectum).": "",
  "What does 'midsagittal plane' mean?": "",
  "A plane that cuts an organ at an angle": "",
  "A sagittal plane that passes exactly through the midline, dividing the body into equal left and right halves": "",
  "A vertical plane dividing the body into front and back": "",
  "A horizontal plane dividing the body into top and bottom": "",
  "A midsagittal (median) plane is a specific type of sagittal plane that runs exactly along the midline of the body, creating perfectly equal left and right halves, unlike a parasagittal plane which is off-center.": "",
  "A medical student examining a cadaver is asked to make a cut that divides the body into front and back halves. Which plane should the student use?": "",
  "Sagittal plane": "",
  "Oblique plane": "",
  "Frontal (coronal) plane": "",
  "Transverse plane": "",
  "The frontal (coronal) plane runs vertically from side to side, dividing the body into anterior (front) and posterior (back) portions, which is exactly what the student needs for this cut.": "",
  "A patient presents to the emergency room after falling on their right side. The doctor notes bruising on the patient's right flank. Using directional terms, the bruised area is _____ to the umbilicus (belly button).": "",
  "Deep": "",
  "The flank (side of the body) is lateral to the umbilicus because it is farther from the midline. The umbilicus sits near the midline, while the flank is off to the side.": "",
  "A nurse is preparing a patient for a spinal tap (lumbar puncture). She positions the patient lying on their side with knees drawn up. The needle will enter the vertebral cavity, which is part of which major body cavity?": "",
  "Abdominopelvic cavity": "",
  "Ventral cavity": "",
  "Dorsal cavity": "",
  "Thoracic cavity": "",
  "The vertebral (spinal) canal is a subdivision of the dorsal body cavity, which also includes the cranial cavity. Together these house and protect the central nervous system.": "",
  "During a physical examination, a physician notes that a patient's heart sounds are best heard on the anterior chest wall. The physician describes the stethoscope placement as on the _____ surface of the thorax.": "",
  "Posterior (dorsal)": "",
  "Ventral (anterior)": "",
  "The front of the chest is the ventral (anterior) surface. In humans, anterior and ventral are interchangeable terms meaning toward the front of the body.": "",
  "A radiologist is reviewing a CT scan that shows cross-sectional images of the abdomen. These images were produced by scanning in which anatomical plane?": "",
  "Transverse (horizontal) plane": "",
  "Standard CT scans produce images in the transverse (horizontal) plane, creating cross-sectional slices that divide the body into superior and inferior portions, though modern scanners can reconstruct images in any plane.": "",
  "A patient with appendicitis reports pain in their lower right abdomen. A medical student correctly identifies this region as part of which body cavity?": "",
  "Cranial cavity": "",
  "The appendix is located in the right lower quadrant of the abdominopelvic cavity, which is the ventral body cavity below the diaphragm that houses the digestive organs, kidneys, and pelvic organs.": "",
  "A surgeon describes a wound as being on the posterior surface of the patient's leg, deep to the skin. In this context, the muscle beneath the wound is _____ to the skin.": "",
  "Superficial": "",
  "Deep means farther from the body surface, toward the interior. Muscles lie deep to (beneath) the skin, while the skin is superficial to (above) the muscles.": "",
  "A paramedic arrives at a scene and finds an unconscious person lying face down. The paramedic reports over the radio that the patient is in the _____ position.": "",
  "Prone": "",
  "Supine": "",
  "Lateral recumbent": "",
  "Anatomical": "",
  "Prone means lying face down, which is the position described. Supine is the opposite, meaning lying face up on the back, and both are important clinical position terms.": "",
  "A nursing student is asked to identify the relationship between the knee and the ankle. Using directional terms, the knee is _____ to the ankle.": "",
  "The knee is proximal to the ankle because it is closer to the trunk (the point of attachment of the lower limb). Proximal and distal are directional terms used specifically for the limbs.": "",
  "A physician is explaining to a patient that their chest X-ray shows fluid accumulation in the space surrounding the lungs. This fluid is within which specific body cavity?": "",
  "Pleural cavity": "",
  "Peritoneal cavity": "",
  "Pericardial cavity": "",
  "The pleural cavities are the spaces surrounding each lung within the thoracic cavity, lined by the visceral and parietal pleural membranes. Fluid accumulation here is called a pleural effusion and can compress the lung.": ""
}